Polymorphism is a key concept in object-oriented programming, including Python. At a high level, it means that different
 classes can define their own version of a method, but you can call that method on objects of different types, and Python will figure out which one to use.

In simpler terms, you can have a method with the same name in different classes, but each class can implement it differently.
That way, you can treat all these different objects in a uniform way (since they share the same method name) but still have their own specific behavior.
For example, imagine a parent class called Animal with a method speak().
Then, you have a Dog class and a Cat class, each implementing speak() differently.
When you call speak() on a Dog object, it barks; when you call it on a Cat object, it meows—yet you’re using the same method name.
